Transfer the Data Format

# Read Original File and Assign it to "data" 

data <- read_excel("data/0_OriginData_World_Development_Indicators.xlsx")

# Pivot longer to convert year columns into a "Year" column

data_long <- data |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("20"), 
    # Select all year columns (2001-2023)
    names_to = "Year",          
    # Move column names to "Year"
    values_to = "Value"
    # Store data values in "Value"
    )        

# Drop NAs contained by these cols

data_long <- data_long |>
  drop_na(`Country Name`, `Country Code`, `Series Code`, `Series Name`)

# Convert Year column to numeric

data_long$Year <- as.numeric(str_extract(data_long$Year, "\\d+"))

# Pivot wider to make Series Name values into separate columns

data_clean <- data_long |>
  select(-"Series Code") |>
  # delete the "Series Code" column
  pivot_wider(names_from = "Series Name", 
              values_from = "Value")

Here, we delete the âSeries Codeâ column, because all the values in it have corresponding value in column âSeries Nameâ. If we donât delete it, all values of the variables would be misaligned and lots of blank rows when pivot_wider using âSeries Nameâ.

# Save the data as an Excel file

# write_xlsx(data_clean, "data/1_world_bank_data_clean.xlsx")

Economic Growth and Labor Market Trends: Insights from GDP, Employment, and Consumption

1. Labor Force Participation and Economic Growth Over Time

ggplot(data_available_clean, aes(x = year, y = lfpr_total_15_64_milo, color = country_name, group = country_name)) +
  geom_line(size = 0.8, alpha=0.8) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=country_name), size=1.5) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(data_available_clean$year), max(data_available_clean$year), by = 5)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  theme_grey() +
  labs(
    title = "Labor Force Participation Rate Over Time",
    subtitle = "Tracking Workforce Engagement Across Countries",
    x = "Year", 
    y = "Labor Force Participation Rate (%)",
    caption = "Source: World Bank Data"
  ) +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Country") +
  
  theme_minimal() +

        panel.grid = element_blank(),

2. GDP Growth Trends Over Time

Economic growth, measured by GDP growth rates, reflects a countryâs overall economic health. By visualizing GDP growth over time, we can identify economic cycles, including periods of expansion, recession, or stagnation.

ggplot(data = data_available_clean, mapping = aes(x = year, y = gdp_growth, fill = country_name)) +
  geom_area(alpha = 0.5, position = "identity") +  # Uses geom_area to fill under the curve
  facet_wrap(~country_name) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(data_available_clean$year), max(data_available_clean$year), by = 5)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(
    title = "GDP Growth Over Time",
    subtitle = "Visualizing Economic Trends Across Countries",
    x = "Year",
    y = "GDP Growth (%)",
    caption = "Source: World Bank Data"
  ) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Blues", name = "Country") +  # Uses a color palette for clarity
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
        panel.grid = element_blank(),

  )

##3. Relationship Between Final Consumption Growth and Labor Force Participation Final consumption, which includes household and government expenditures, is a major driver of GDP. A high labor force participation rate (LFPR) should, in theory, lead to strong consumption growth, as more people in the workforce typically have greater disposable income. However, if LFPR is high but consumption growth is weak, it could indicate low wages, high savings rates, or economic uncertainty. To analyze this, we plot final consumption growth against LFPR.

ggplot(data = data_available_clean, mapping = aes(x = lfpr_total_15_64_milo, y = final_cons_growth, color = country_name, size = gdp_growth)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +  # Scatter plot to visualize data points
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black", linetype = "dashed") +  # Adds trend line
  facet_wrap(~country_name) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(
    title = "Final Consumption Growth vs. Labor Force Participation",
    subtitle = "Examining the Link Between Workforce Engagement and Consumer Demand",
    x = "Labor Force Participation Rate (%)", 
    y = "Final Consumption Growth (%)",
    caption = "Source: World Bank Data"
  ) +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Country") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
        panel.grid = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),  
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 12),  
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12),  
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12),  
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 12),
        legend.position = "bottom",
        axis.line = element_line(color = "black")  # Ensures both x-axis and y-axis lines are visible
  )
